<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORE DEFENSE INDUSTRY LAYOFFS IN THE WORKS; 
</P>
<P>
AEROSPACE: GENERAL DYNAMICS WILL LET UP TO 2,000 WORKERS GO. IT ALSO PLANS TO 
CONSOLIDATE UNITS IN POMONA AND RANCHO CUCAMONGA. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RALPH VARTABEDIAN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
General Dynamics said Monday that it will lay off 1,500 to 2,000 workers in the 
Los Angeles area by the end of 1991 and consolidate two divisions in Pomona and 
Rancho Cucamonga. 
</P>
<P>
The St. Louis-based defense giant blamed the cutbacks on declining defense 
budgets and on the negative effects of a broad Pentagon procurement policy to 
seek second production sources for weapons. 
</P>
<P>
Ralph Hawes, the firm's executive vice president, said Monday that the company 
may lay off 600 to 1,000 workers by the end of this year but has made no 
decision about closing any of its missile plants. 
</P>
<P>
The firm's Valley Systems division in Rancho Cucamonga employs 3,500, and its 
Pomona division employs 5,700, including 1,600 out of state. Both divisions 
produce tactical missiles. The Pomona division already has laid off 560 workers 
this year and is down from a peak of 8,000 three years ago. 
</P>
<P>
"It is very clear that there is going to be less business out there," Hawes 
said in a telephone interview Monday. "It is really beginning to hit home." 
</P>
<P>
The aerospace downturn overtaking General Dynamics is expected to last at least 
through the mid-1990s, by which point the California economy would have lost an 
estimated 110,000 direct defense jobs, according to economic forecasters 
DRI-McGraw Hill. 
</P>
<P>
In the past year, virtually every major prime contractor in Southern California 
has been forced to cut back employment, either because of a drop in business or 
because it wants to flee to lower-cost areas of the nation. 
</P>
<P>
Hughes Aircraft eliminated more than 9,000 jobs last year. Lockheed may cut as 
many as 8,000 jobs over the next few years. McDonnell Douglas is slashing 8,000 
jobs this year. Northrop is trimming 3,000 jobs this year. Only TRW and 
Rockwell International have yet to order sizable layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
General Dynamics is the nation's second-largest defense contractor and has 
103,000 employees at facilities stretching from a submarine shipyard in the 
Boston area to a rocket plant in San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
Even though Pomona and Rancho Cucamonga are among the firm's smaller 
operations, they have accounted for about half of the corporation's layoffs 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
The reason for the disproportionate effect is that tactical missile programs 
are being sharply cut back by the Pentagon, even as it seeks to preserve the 
$62.8 billion B-2 Stealth bomber program and other higher cost weapons. 
</P>
<P>
In addition, the General Dynamics operations have been severely hurt by a broad 
Pentagon policy in recent years to seek second production sources for its 
weapons. Every major program at the two divisions was slated for second 
sourcing, Hawes noted. 
</P>
<P>
The Navy selected Raytheon to compete on the Standard missile and General 
Electric to compete on the Phalanx shipboard gun. The Army selected Raytheon to 
compete on the Army Stinger missile. 
</P>
<P>
Now, both Raytheon and General Electric are behind schedule in learning how to 
build those systems and have yet to be "certified" for production, even though 
the Pentagon is continuing to award contracts to the firms, Hawes charged. 
</P>
<P>
"They are both substantially late in getting qualified," he said. 
</P>
<P>
Moreover, even though the Pentagon has a new policy of curtailing second source 
competitions, it can not terminate the General Dynamics competitions until the 
second sources have been qualified so they can compete for a final buyout of 
production, Hawes charged. 
</P>
<P>
"From a business point of view, you have to question the sanity of it," Hawes 
said. 
</P>
<P>
As a result, Hawes said, General Dynamics is now attempting to cut its costs so 
it can eventually win the future competitions, assuming the competition learns 
how to build the products. 
</P>
<P>
General Dynamics said about 600 of the 1,500 to 2,000 due to be eliminated will 
come from reducing duplication once the divisions are combined. 
</P>
<P>
When General Dynamics decided to open the Rancho Cucamonga operation in 1985 in 
the heyday of the Reagan Administration defense buildup, it was to relieve the 
growth at the Pomona operation. 
</P>
<P>
But the Pentagon decision to seek second sources left General Dynamics with 
excess factory capacity, since it would have to share production. In Phalanx 
guns, for example, General Dynamics tooled up for production of 10 systems per 
month, but under dual sourcing production is likely to be two or three per 
month. 
</P>
<P>
It is not clear how the company will eliminate surplus factory space. Though 
Hawes expressed the sort of dissatisfaction with the California business 
climate that is now commonplace in the industry, he ruled out a total closure 
of the California facilities. 
</P>
<P>
"I don't have any immediate plans for a wholesale move out of California, but I 
would certainly have to say that the trend is to move out of California on a 
long-term basis," Hawes said. 
</P>
<P>
For one thing, the firm has invested tremendously in its Pomona plant over the 
years. In addition, it is partly owned by the Navy, which helps lower costs. 
The Rancho Cucamonga plant is owned by General Dynamics. The two divisions also 
operate plants in Camden, Ark., and on a Navajo Indian Reservation. Hawes said 
the company recently opened a small plant in the Imperial Valley, where wages 
are lower, to see if it can continue to do business in California at all. So 
far, 100 workers are located at the facility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
DEFENSE INDUSTRY -- LABOR RELATIONS; AEROSPACE INDUSTRY -- LABOR RELATIONS; 
DEFENSE INDUSTRY -- LAYOFFS; AEROSPACE INDUSTRY -- LAYOFFS; GENERAL DYNAMICS 
CORP; AEROSPACE INDUSTRY -- LOS ANGELES COUNTY; DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE (U.S.) -- 
CONTRACTS; UNITED STATES -- BUDGET; DEFENSE SPENDING 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
