<P>
BOY'S QUICK ACTION SAVES 2 FROM FIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TUSTIN 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A 12-year-old boy escorted his 4- and 5-year-old sisters from a burning 
apartment building on Monday and then dialed 911 for help, fire officials said. 
</P>
<P>
The 8:17 a.m. fire was started by one of the children playing with matches in a 
bedroom closet. 
</P>
<P>
The fire caused about $60,000 damage to the apartment complex at 120 Nisson 
Road, Orange County Fire Department Spokeswoman Kathleen Cha said. No one was 
injured. 
</P>
<P>
Cha said the children were home alone when the fire broke out. Fire officials 
said the boy acted quickly to ensure the safety of his sisters and notify 
authorities of the blaze. 
</P>
<P>
"He did a real good job of remaining calm and doing the right things," said 
Fire Department Capt. Dan Young, who added that the boy had recently completed 
a junior fire safety program at his school. 
</P>
<P>
Fire officials have not identified which child was playing with matches. 
</P>
<P>
Fire and police officials on Monday were investigating the circumstances of the 
fire and why the children were left unsupervised. 
</P>
