<HEADLINE>
<P>
PRESIDENT OF AMERICAN HEALTH SERVICES RESIGNS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ANNE MICHAUD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEWPORT BEACH 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The American Health Services Corp. chief executive credited with building the 
company into a $30-million operator of medical imaging centers resigned on 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
In announcing that S. Lewis Meyer had stepped down as president, chief 
executive and a director, company officials offered no reason for the 
resignation. 
</P>
<P>
American Health named E. Larry Atkins, the company's executive vice president 
and chief operating officer for the past four years, to replace Meyer. 
</P>
<P>
In a statement Monday, American Health expressed its "appreciation for Meyer's 
efforts." Meyer could not be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
American Health contracts with hospitals and other health-care providers to 
supply diagnostic equipment for such procedures as magnetic resonance imaging 
and computerized tomography at medical centers in 12 states and Puerto Rico. 
Eleven of the centers are in California. 
</P>
<P>
Atkins said he plans to encourage the company's expansion by opening new 
centers. He said the number of centers is expected to increase to 40 by the end 
of this year, from nine in 1988. Twelve more centers are scheduled to open in 
1991. 
</P>
<P>
The publicly traded company, which employs 158 people, posted strong results 
for 1989. Net income was $910,145, contrasted with a loss of $4.7 million for 
the previous year, which included a loss of $4.1 million from discontinued 
operations. For the first quarter ended March 31, 1990, the company posted net 
income of $325,508, up from $106,666 for the like period in 1989. According to 
company spokesman Bradley Serwin, revenues for this year are projected at $30 
million. 
</P>
<P>
Meyer had guided the 8-year-old company for the past 6 1/2 years. Before 
joining American Health, he was chief executive of Datatron Inc., a Tustin 
computer equipment company. 
</P>
<P>
Atkins was president from 1979 to 1986 of Dallas-based American Medical 
International Diagnostic Services Inc., which provides mobile diagnostic 
imaging. Previously, he established a product distribution network in Europe, 
India and the Middle East for Technicare Corp. of Amsterdam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
AMERICAN HEALTH SERVICES CORP; MANAGEMENT; RESIGNATIONS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA080790-0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 258763 </DOCID>
