<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHLAND; 
</P>
<P>
3 GIRLS RESCUED ON MOUNTAIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FROM TIMES WIRE SERVICES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Three teen-age girls from Orange who got lost Monday while hiking during a 
church outing in the rugged Angeles National Forest were rescued by authorities 
at dawn today, unharmed but shaken from their night under lightning and 
thunder-filled skies. 
</P>
<P>
The girls -- identified as Debbie Johnson, 13, Kristen Lawrence, 14, and 
Christina Roberts, 15 -- spent the night huddled together under leaves and pine 
trees and required no medical attention, said Los Angeles County Sheriff's Sgt. 
Bobby Denham at the Antelope Valley substation. 
</P>
<P>
Other officers said the girls, camping with a Mormon church group from Orange, 
had left their campsite about 5 p.m. Monday bound for Jackson Lake, 1 1/2 miles 
away. On their return trip they ventured off the trail -- intentionally -- and 
became lost. By nightfall, Denham said, a "huge downpour" struck. 
</P>
<P>
The girls heard a helicopter at daybreak and hiked to a clearing where they 
could be seen, Denham said. Members of the department's volunteer search and 
rescue team found them at 7:15 a.m. near Inspiration Point, about a half-mile 
from the Angeles Crest Highway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
