<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
S.F. HOSPITAL TO CLOSE OBSTETRICS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FROM TIMES WIRE SERVICES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SAN FRANCISCO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The oldest Roman Catholic hospital on the West Coast will end 133 years of 
delivering babies in November. 
</P>
<P>
St. Mary's Hospital said it is closing down its obstetrics unit because it 
delivered fewer than 800 babies in the last year, although it was not losing 
money. 
</P>
<P>
Hospitals traditionally lose money when their number of births falls below 
1,200 a year. St. Mary's has been shifting emphasis toward heart surgery and 
orthopedic care. Both are more lucrative for a hospital than obstetrical care. 
</P>
</TEXT>
